    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-10-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-10-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="1269"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1269">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/10–2354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Assistant Secretary of
                        State for European Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MLT1"
                        >Merchant</persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d1269fn1">This meeting was held at
                        the British Embassy.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1954-10-23">October 23, 1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Indochina</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Sir Anthony Eden</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Sir <persName>Harold Caccia</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>Denis Allen</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>During the meeting of the Secretary with <persName corresp="#p_ESA1"
                        >Eden</persName> on other subjects reported separately, he took occasion to
                    inform <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> in detail on development our
                    thinking and plans regarding Vietnam. The Secretary told him that he would be
                    happy to have him join him at his meeting later in the day with <persName
                        corresp="#p_MFP1">Mendes-France</persName> on this subject. <persName
                        corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> accepted with appreciation and then read a
                    cable from Sir <persName>Hubert Graves</persName> in Saigon which indicated that
                    he fully shared <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName>’s deep concern over
                    the existing political situation in South Vietnam but in conclusion plumped for
                        <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Tam</persName> as successor to <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d1269fn2">The source
                        text is accompanied by a one-page summary not printed, of the position of
                        Ambassador <persName>Graves</persName>. A handwritten notation by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> on that document states that
                            <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> presented it to <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> on Oct. 23 and also gave a copy to
                        Premier <persName corresp="#p_MFP1">Mendés-France</persName>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In general <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> expressed full support for
                    our position but the inference seemed clear that the UK is principally concerned
                    with Laos and has little confidence that the position in South Vietnam can be
                    saved.</p>
            </div>
